segments.text: She was here for commencement?
Yeah, she was here for commencement.
She grew up in the next town.
She grew up in the town of Menard.
Oh, okay.
I saved her from a life at the University of Texas.
She was a junior at the University of Texas when we got married.
We decided that we'd wait and let her finish up her degree at some other time, which she's never done.
Mm-hmm.
And we lived in what was known as the new project houses.
Yes.
$37.50 a month.
Describe that.
Oh, beautiful facilities, really, compared to what else we had.
These were the, well, they're torn down now, but there were tennis courts in there.
But they were very nice, a two-story apartment, and we were on the second story.
Had a nice living room, kitchen,
dining room, living room together, and two bedrooms.
And it was $37.50, and that was great.
Furnished?
Yeah, furnished.
Oh, my.
Yeah.
No.
But $19.50, that was very reasonable.
And we had no automobile.
And you were in a small little community of other young marrieds.
Right.
Now, were these the old project house structures that had been redone?
No, these were new, relatively new.
The old project houses were really trashy stuff.
They'd been worn out for years.
These had been there for a while.
I think they were built during the early part of the war.
Reckon how many couples were over there at one time?
How many could... Let's see, there'd be four couples to the building, and there were probably about...
I'm going to say 30 or 40 buildings, so quite a few.
100 or so couples.
What kind of community activities did you young marrieds have?
Very nice.
It was really good.
We had either penny ante poker games where you carried the pennies in a jar, you know, or a bridge or those sort of things and shared dinners with each other.
Picnics.
Picnics, go to the events, go to the movies.
At that time, well, we were one of the last ones to get an automobile, but next door neighbors had an automobile, and we'd go to the movies.
At that time, they had the Midnight Surprise movies.
That guy in?
No, this was down in downtown Bryant, Palace Theater, whatever it was down there.
It was always a surprise, but always a very good movie.
But it started at midnight on Saturday night, so we'd take those in.
Let's see, picnics there?
Did y'all sometimes have an outdoor cookout?
Oh, yeah, we would.
Somebody would have friends on the coast and get a big bunch of shrimp or a big bunch of oysters in and have...
You know, sort of a communal feed.
What kind of shopping opportunities were there at Southgate then?
There was a small grocery store there at Southgate.
There was the cleaners.
And the drugstore.
And the drugstore.
What was their name?
Maitley.
Maitley's Pharmacy.
Yeah, Maitley's Pharmacy.
Then Maitley and his wife had that dress shop.
It was very convenient.
If you didn't have an automobile, it was very convenient.
You could have everything you really had right there, close to you.
Right, so you finish your degree in one year, then what?
Then I was...
contacted by a fellow who had called John McNeely.

They were setting up, this was New York City, they were setting up a business, or they had the business already going, called Industrial Commodity Corporation, but they were looking for someone who had a background in ag research, and particularly in livestock.
And so they came down and talked to me, and it sounded like a good opportunity to do something different.
see the big city.
So we took it for the sum total of $5,000 a year.
Moved to the big city and moved.
Rich, our older son, was born here.
And I took off in a trailer, pulling a trailer with all of our, what little household goods we had, and drove to New York.
And Doc said the baby came up, flew up.
Now, this is 1951 or 2?
No, this was late 52.
And you were up there how long?
I was up there a little over two years.
And finally decided that we lived in a little town on Long Island called Belmore.
On the Long Island Railway.
So it was an easy commute in, except it took an hour each way.
So I caught the 657 every morning.
They get into work at 9 o'clock.
I said, it took two hours.
And they came in about 7 o'clock that night.
I finally realized that I had a little baby girl that I had not seen in the daylight since she was born, except occasionally on the weekend.
So we left there and moved.
They set up a
Regional Livestock Marketing Research Organization in Denver, which is sponsored by the 12 western states.
And at that time it was called the 12 Western States and Texas, but we weren't officially a western state at that time.
But it was headquartered operationally out of Colorado State, but our offices were in Denver.
So I moved down there and

stayed there until 50 spring of our winter of 56 moved down here then and what were you going to do we were setting up the big problem that they were that we were trying to address was how to forecast the market conditions for feeder livestock coming off of it coming off of the ranges how to how to anticipate what the volume are going to be and some of the conditions and weights were going to be how the livestock
coming in off of the winter ranges and fall ranges and the cattle feeding market.
The reason it was located in Denver because that's where most of the cattle feeding was taking place up in that area.
All right, and you come here to do what?
Came here then to work with, when I came here, I came down one time to see some people in Ag Eco, John McNeely, and he said they were starting a new program

over here called the something like the Texas Transportation Institute and Fred Benson was the honcho of it and they were looking for somebody to join up with that program thought it might be a good opportunity to come over and see him so they had to talk to him over and talk to Fred and he said well they were looking for somebody they wanted to look at
the customer needs in transportation.
We'd always been concerned about the producer of transportation, the people that were doing the actual physical work of moving people and goods and so forth.
And we really had not paid that much attention to what the people who were using the transportation really wanted.
So we said, we've got Mr. Thomas H. McDonald, who was chief of the old Bureau of Public Roads for many, many years, 34 years, I think.
And he's going to be sort of, he and Gib Gilchrist are the ones that sort of put this together, and they're looking for somebody to sort of take this program over and run with it.
That's Mr. McDonnell, by the way.
Did you ever know him, Louie?
He was a very nice guy, very sharp.
I don't believe so.
So Fred said, now,
I'm going to be working over there, but I didn't have a decision.
It's going to be on whether Mr. MacDonald and Mr. Gilchrist would, uh, they'll be the ones making the decision whether to hire you.
So I went over and visited with them and, uh, went back to Denver and got a call.
Yeah, they'd like to have me and that Fred Benson would want to deal with.
And so Fred, uh, had then wrote me a letter and said that, uh,
They had agreed that the position was open and that they'd like to have me and that they were willing to pay $7,000 a year.
I said, Fred, Mr. Benson.
We didn't call him Fred then.
Mr. Benson, I just left a job in New York that was paying me $12,500 and moved to Denver to take one for $10,000.
Now I'm going to move back down here to take one for $7,000.
At least get it up to $7,200.
It's even a little better.
He said, I hate to tell you this, but that's all the money I've got.
And said, not only that, we've already turned in the budgets for next year.
And so you won't get a raise next year either.
So I said, OK. We were anxious to start to get back here.
And so we took the job again.
And what was the name of the organization at that time?
Well, it started out, it was really the organization was created in 1950, and the original document had it as the Texas Institute of Transportation, until they looked at...
The acronym.
The acronym.
And so I was still somewhere where we had the old original document where it's all been redlined on and that's been changed over to the Texas Transportation Institute.
And it reported to, organizationally, to the office of whom?
Reported to Fred, well, Fred Benson was the, at that time it was called the executive director, not director, no, executive officer.
In engineering.
Oh, and then, all right.
Fred was, when we first came here, Fred was a professor of civil engineering, and he had responsibility for some of the operations of TTI.
All right, but your, so your appointed title then was director of TTI?
No, I was an associate research economist.
Oh, okay, and was he the director of?
Well, he was the executive officer.
We didn't have a director at that time.
Just make believe that I didn't know Fred Benson.
Describe him in personality and appearance and habit and so forth.
As you probably know, Fred was a Navy captain.
Navy captain?
Mm-hmm.
No, I did not.
Oh, yes.
And he was always, of course, he always looked like a movie star.
Mm-hmm.
Mm-hmm.
a very personable fellow, not an effusive type.
He was as straight a shooter as I ever met in my life.
Anything he told you he would do, as far as I know, he never backed down on it.
He always came through anything he told you that he would try to do, even then he would try to do it.
But he said, now, you're going to be working on, he said, I want Mr. McDonald to sort of be with you on all this, because he's been involved in all this, and it's been of particular interest of his.
So we worked, I think, until late 57 when Mr. McDonald died.
And of course, by that time, Mr. Gilchrist was getting pretty feeble.
He was housebound most of the time.
So I took most of my work over.
to his house and worked with him over there.
Now what was his official...
He really didn't have an official title.

He was former chancellor, but he... TTI was really put together by Mr. McDonnell, Fred Benson who was here, Mr. Gilchrist who was chancellor, and Mr. DeWitt Greer who was head of the highway department.
The three of those really conceived the idea of having a research institute that could really help
move transportation forward.
All three of them had a long-standing interest in transportation.
Now, Benson was out of mechanical engineering?
Civil.
But public transportation was and all was one of his... Highway transportation, particularly he was in the physical side, in materials and construction, that sort of side of transportation.

Now, it wasn't long until Fred was moved up to head, when Cy Sandestead retired, Fred was moved up to head the Civil Engineering Department, and was, at that same time, was also made director of TTI, a position that he held until about 62, when Jack Keese then
was named, Fred moved up to Dean, and Jack Keese was made director.
Where was TTI physically located?
Right up here on the absolute corner of Spence and Ross.
It was a little small two-story building called the Highway Research Center.
When we moved into it, or when I got here, I think there were four of us.
So it was a building that was plenty big for four people.
And it was primarily a research organization.
We had two research projects underway, both of which we got finished successfully.
What were they?

The customer requirements in transportation, which is the one that I had, and then there was one on the effects of highway transportation on land values that a fellow named Bill Atkins, who is dead now, directed.
Who were in those early days, who were the key people in Austin that were supportive of TTI?
DeWitt Greer was the number one supporter.
He's the one that, and he supported us over a substantial amount of resistance from some of his second level people that really didn't see the need for research.

and in any in any manner in fact one of them that we were told who that Mr. Greer said that when we had a research project that he wanted done he said now you take it down and work with so-and-so down here in this department and he'll be the one that you work with so we went down and talked to him and he said I'll tell you what boy
this, be sure you print that on some soft paper and bring it over to me that way so I'll have some real use for it.
Not real encouraging, not real encouraging, but we did have the support of the administration and that always helps a lot who can use it correctly.
Were there any other states that had anything that could serve as a model for TTI?
Not really.
There have been, since then, a number of states that have come in.
We have been used as a model for a bunch of states.
Pennsylvania's used us almost exclusively as a model.
Virginia has been doing it for many, many years.

They've got a little different, most of them have a little different twist to a lot of things, but we were sort of the first one, and I guess the first one that was set up as a part of a university system.
specifically to do research in transportation.
And in the 50s and 60s, what were some of the major projects that y'all did that really helped to move it up in importance and credibility?
During that period, we had the Highway Revenue Act of 19...
58, I believe it was, which for the first time made federal funds available to the states to do work.
This was an old interstate system that was created back in the old Eisenhower program.

And so one of the big things we're doing is when you quit doing what you're doing now, that is dealing with local roads or regional roads, just going from this city to that one, and it's kind of this cross-country

uh super highway system uh to begin to look at what effect is this going to have on those cities that you're either going through on the bigger cities or that you're bypassing those small ones that you just go by and leave them sitting out on the limb so some of the earliest work that we did was in the effects of these bypasses on smaller cities from
cities the size of Merkel out by Abilene down to Baytown and some of those like that and to look at what does 410 do to the whole land value economic activity in San Antonio.
So we did studies on a large number of those.
Also we began to look at for the first time to look at the fact we've been doing
how we work for all these years, and we've been using the same materials and using them the same way.
We've been cookbooking everything.
We do it because you put so much of this and so much of that, and this is the way it's done, and practical experience shows that may be working out pretty well, but we find out that really it isn't.
So we don't really have much, and we're still working on that problem, by the way, but we've really not improved our whole materials application systems like we should.
So we started working in that using some things like looking at new plasticers and additives that you could put in asphalt.
People sort of assumed that asphalt was a common material.
That is, it was all the same.
That's asphalt.
Asphalt's asphalt and they're all just alike.
Absolutely wrong.
Asphalt is what you get out of a barrel of crude
that's left in the bottom after you've taken everything you want out of the rest of it.
So it's going to be a combination of a hundred different things in different quantities.
So we're still trying to characterize and get ways that you can physically identify those differences and find out physically then which ones of these chemical compositions work and which ones don't.
As you can see, it becomes a very, very big problem that we've been working on for many years.
All right, so Fred Benson as dean, he was supportive.
Right.
And as the years went on, now four decades, did TTI remain closest to engineering?
And were there any other institutions that ever tried to combat TTI to undo it?
Not really.
Not any that I know of that overtly tried to do it.
Internally, at that time, I know Dean Benson
And I really don't know the background of why this is so, but Dean Benson felt that he probably was not getting the support that he would like to have from Dr. Harrington.
Now, whether this was because of a Gilchrist-Harrington problem or what, but...
post-retirement era sort of devoted to transportation and TTI.
But as far as, we had good support from the administration of the highway department at that time.
And so that helped tremendously.
That gave us a base support in research, which is the essential element that anybody going into a structured research program like we're in now, where you have that many people involved,
You have to have some sort of a base you can count on from year to year.
Now, you're going to bring in outside, other outside money, but you have to have that base to really keep it going from year to year.
Fred was soon, not too long, in 1975, no,
I'm trying to get my people and dates together.
He was made dean.
Jack Keese was made director at that time, but Fred still, we still reported to Fred.
Now
As you probably, and I hope you recall, we've gone through all of the different variations of how you administered the system and the A&M University.
And later, that's one of the things I want you to comment about, which you think is better.
All right, but as he becomes dean, then you'll have another supporter in the key location.
How did you introduce the TTI to Earl Rutter?
Well, this...
Earl Rutter was, I had known Earl Rutter for years and years, so that helped some.
Well, not necessarily helped, but it did give an entree.
And he was very supportive.
We've always sort of taken the practical approach to the research, that it's not highly theoretical, that it's going to be put on a bookshelf and left alone, but it's going to be useful to somebody.
And he recognized that, and he became active.
He addressed every one of our short courses that we had and became very active in the things that we were doing.
Got some real lessons in writing speeches for President Rutter.
It was very interesting.
He is the most effective man I ever saw, indeed, in short.
one-on-one type groups and with smart, sharp groups, but public speaking was not his forte.
Did he give you all any advice in what kinds of speeches he wanted written?
Yeah, he did.
Can you share that?
He said that, one, you don't put those big, long, complicated words in there that are hard to pronounce.
He wants it in short bites, I mean, not bites at that time, but short sentences where you can
get the point across without having to go into a great deal of elaboration, and don't be long-winded.
Keep the paragraphs down to a short thing.
Just a good... See, he had...
I really don't remember what dates this was, but he had taken a course in speaking under Dr. Hurd and sent out a memo to all of the...
system parts and university administrators that he thought this was such a good idea that he would encourage everybody else to do that.
So I did that too.
I took that course under Dr. Harrison Hurt and still consider him to be a real good friend.
He's a very, very fine fellow.
You said that you knew Mr. Rutter before he became president.
Describe that acquaintance.
Well, I mentioned before that he grew up in the Eden area, which is close to where my family was.
We were in Junction.
And my two sisters and his, actually went to school at the same time he did in Eden, and then knew his wife, Margaret, very well.
They were sort of peer group.
And then my brother ran his ranch for her.
a good number of years, immediately after World War II.
So while we were not old-time big drinking buddies, I had known him and knew who he was.
He knew who I was.
Chick still...
Describe Mrs.
Rudder as you all knew her as a young person.
Well, she was...
I didn't really know her that well.
My two older sisters are quite a bit older than I am.
They, they knew her quite well.
She was, she was a, they lived on the ranch called, she was a Williamson and the ranch was a very nice ranch located between Hext and London and it's still there.
She and, she has one brother still living, Rusty, and he has a part of the ranch too, the original part of the ranch, but
They've been a solid old ranching family.
She went to school in, say, Menard and then Eden, I think.
I don't know whether that's when she and Earl met in that period of time or not.
She told me that she met him really because her brother had gone to JTAC at the same time Mr. Rutter did.
He brought his yearbook home, and she said, when I saw the picture of that handsome guy, he's six years older than she, and she said, we had a few dates when I was a freshman at the university.
But by the time I'm a junior, she said, we began to date a lot, and seniors were serious.
He was then the football coach, and she got a job teaching as a first year teacher, and I believe she said the fall of 36.
at Brady, making $100 a month.
He was making $135, and they got married the next June.
She said Earl had saved $80, so she said, I got married on $80 in faith.
She said, I thought that he was the handsomest, that picture was the handsomest looking boy I'd ever seen.
All right, so...
you had this acquaintance with Mr. Rutter and he became also a strong supporter.
Were there any, did y'all, did anybody ever try to throw rocks in the road, pun intended, for TTI here on campus?
I think mostly we were ignored pretty well.
We didn't really,
bother anybody in the terms that we weren't cutting into anybody else's territory.

I guess the most friction that we have had has probably been with our closest ally, and that's civil engineering, because we do have so many joint appointments and differences between, always comes up differences between when the academic budgets go in and then when the system part budgets go in.
You're operating off of different funding sources, and you have different sets of requirements of what you can and cannot give in the way of merit increases and that sort of thing.
So that always presents another problem.
So that is the main type of thing.
As far as I know, we have not really been considered either pro or con by other engineering departments, primarily outside of that.
because we don't have that strong relationship with them.
We do have a number of joint employees from other departments on campus, but it's generally a one or two from each department and not a big number.

So it's not a major problem that if we get a research project that's going to demand three full-time employees and we take them out of the department, where are they going to get those people to teach their courses?
You know, that sort of problem.
And it is a problem.
Now, was it a line item appropriation down through the years?
We went in, we originally went in as a joint budget because of Dean Benson was operating both TTI and TEAS, as well as the College of Engineering.
So we submitted a joint budget to the legislature, which was TEAS and TTI.
